Example Problem with Solution:

Use rbinom() to generate two random samples of size 10,000 from the binomial distribution. For the first sample, use p = 0.45 and n = 10. For the second sample, use p = 0.55 and n = 10. Convert the sample frequencies to sample proportions and compute the mean number of successes for each sample. Present these statistics.

set.seed(123)
sample.one <- table(rbinom(10000, 10, 0.45)) / 10000
sample.two <- table(rbinom(10000, 10, 0.55)) / 10000

successes <- seq(0, 10)

round(sum(sample.one*successes), digits = 1) # [1] 4.5
## [1] 4.5
round(sum(sample.two*successes), digits = 1) # [1] 5.5
## [1] 5.5

Question: How do the simulated expectations compare to calculated binomial expectations?

Answer: The calculated binomial expectations are 10(0.45) = 4.5 and 10(0.55) = 5.5. After rounding the simulated results, the same values are obtained.

Essay Question (2 points): Discuss the sex distribution of abalones. What stands out about the distribution of abalones by CLASS?

Answer: When SEX (Female, Infant, Male) plotted against the CLASS (A1, A2, A3, A4 & A5) it shows us that most # of Infants are counted, as expected, in A1 and A2, and continously decrease in number after reaching its peak at A2, from 133 down to 19 at A5. The distribution of Female and Male Abalones are considerably similar to each other. While Female abalones (this also correlates with the answer of Question #1), both SEX types show increase until they reach A3, then drop and remain relatively close in number to each other at A4 and A5. It is important to note that there are still Infants in oldest/highest CLASS, A5, and the difference between Female and Male, which is seen distinctly until A3, almost disappears by A5. So, at the last CLASS both SEXs approximately represent half of the adult abalones count.

Essay Question (2 points): How does the variability in this plot differ from the plot in (a)? Compare the two displays. Keep in mind that SHUCK is a part of WHOLE. Consider the location of the different age classes.

Answer: Overall looking at the scatterplot, we can see that there is a positive correlation between Whole Weight and Shuck Weight. As expected, the younger abalones have the minimum weight, yet we would also expect not to see any infant abalones with 150+ weight, therefore we can state that there are some infant outliers. Also, as the weight increases, we observe a more spread scatter throughout adult abalones in (b), again indicating more outliers. Overall, the variability is lower in the plot (b) as SHUCK is a part of the WHOLE, we see a more uniform plot.

Base R or ggplot2 may be used.

Essay Question (5 points) How well do you think these variables would perform as predictors of age? Explain.

Answer: I think both variables are good predictors of age. In the first row of the plots, we see the boxplot of age groups against volume, and there is a noticeable correlation. As we go further to the older age groups (A3 onwards), we can see that the volume and whole also increases. A similar situation is observed in the second set of charts, scatterplots, which also show a positive correlation in regards to the rings. Therefore, we can conclusively state that both age and rings are positively correlated with volume and whole.

Section 6: (11 points) Conclusions from the Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA).

Conclusions

Essay Question 1) (5 points) Based solely on these data, what are plausible statistical reasons that explain the failure of the original study? Consider to what extent physical measurements may be used for age prediction.

Answer: In my opinion, a similar pattern we see throughout all genders is the biggest issue. There is no definite difference between trends of Infants and Adults, which makes it difficult to see the distinction in gender and age groups. The second reason for the failure of the original study may be the number of outliers. I think it would be useful to clean and normalize the data before going through the analysis, yet this is not the significant reason, as I still believe that the similarity in the trends between genders and ages would prevent us from having a conclusive analysis. The weight and volume seem to be the best indicators of age, as they show a positive correlation with aging throughout the study.

Essay Question 2) (3 points) Do not refer to the abalone data or study. If you were presented with an overall histogram and summary statistics from a sample of some population or phenomenon and no other information, what questions might you ask before accepting them as representative of the sampled population or phenomenon?

Answer: Initially, I would want to know more about the context and the background of the study. For example, how the data was collected, when it was collected, the duration of the data collection period, parameters, metrics, how the population, as well as the sample group, was chosen, etc. are critical information to know to understand a dataset better. Once I get more details of the context, I would look into some other examples of studies/data on that specific field, and ideally compare the summarise of both to check the integrity and validity of the dataset in hand. This would also allow me to see which paths have been explored previously, which variables may be the most significant, and lessons learned.

Essay Question 3) (3 points) Do not refer to the abalone data or study. What do you see as difficulties analyzing data derived from observational studies? Can causality be determined? What might be learned from such studies?

Answer: To answer first two questions, I think analyzing data on observational studies is difficult and tricky because they do are not helpful and viable to prove causality. Observational studies are great for understanding underlying correlations between variables and trends, but as they do not have data or control over the unmeasurable external factors (environmental, helth, location, etc. related) they will not allow the analysis to determine any clear cause-and-effect relationship. So, no, I dont believe causation can be determined from such studies. I think, referring back to my answer for Question #2 above, we would need more information and direction regarding the context of the data, which then can be used to indentify possible external factors to include in the study. This may be a beneficial step to take in order to come close to finding a cause for certain type of observation of trends/behaviours withing the data.
